The paper focuses on replicating biological visual sensing in artificial systems, specifically for the task of visual motion estimation. This suggests that the paper is likely to belong to the computer vision (cs.CV) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of neuromorphic engineering, which involves the use of artificial neural networks, and therefore the paper may also belong to the neural and evolutionary computing (cs.NE) sub-category. The paper also discusses the potential applications of this technology in robotics, suggesting that it may belong to the robotics (cs.RO) sub-category. The paper also discusses the progression of works from early attempts to modern state-of-the-art, suggesting that it may belong to the artificial intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of machine learning techniques, suggesting that it may also belong to the machine learning (cs.LG) sub-category.
